ant] Covered:\n[assistant] - `CacheProperties` common and provider-specific public settings.\n[assistant] - `CacheManagerCustomizers` generic type-specific customization behavior.\n[assistant] - Spring Boot auto-configuration discovery via `ImportCandidates`.\n[assistant] - `CacheAutoConfiguration` with `@EnableCaching`.\n[assistant] - Simple/concurrent-map cache auto-configuration.\n[assistant] - Generic cache auto-configuration from user-provided `Cache` beans.\n[assistant] - No-op cache auto-configuration.\n[assistant] - Backoff when a user `CacheManager` is provided.\n[assistant] \n[assistant] No build files were modified, and I did not compile or run tests per instructions.\n[assistant-event] text_end\n[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Examining cache configuration**\\n\\nI’m thinking about a potential issue with the Backoff for the user’s cache manager. It looks like the CacheAutoConfiguration is conditional, relying on the absence of a CacheManager bean. If a CacheManager exists, it seems that the entire auto-configuration is skipped. But I’m wondering if the user’s configuration is processed before the auto-configuration kicks in. Hm, that could lead to some tricky scenarios, and I probably need to clarify that!\\n\\n**Evaluating application context**\\n\\nI'm considering how the ApplicationContextRunner interacts with the user config and auto-configuration. I wonder if this setup will properly register user beans before creating CacheProperties. It seems like the test might only be focusing on CacheManager, which could lead to potential issues with ImportCandidates. I really need to double-check if CacheAutoConfiguration is included, especially given the resource structure. Before finalizing, maybe I should reassess if running tests is even necessary.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0c5e12bf1a741d6c016a3f5a5654188196ab14f422a8237ad4\\\",\\\"type\\